{
  "texts": [
    "Hence, they have the proper function of altering and modulating our emotivity, in a way that nicely fits Piredda's characterization.",
    "8 And it is likely that their proper function is that of altering their users' feelings, rather than their motivational or evaluative states.",
    "So, relying on Viola's (2021) taxonomy, affective artificial agents could be characterized as feeling artifacts: Replika may help a lone person feel loved, thereby easing their social distress (Skjuve et al. 2021), and Pepper may be used to entertain children during boring shopping mall sessions (Aaltonen et al. 2017).",
    "These observations are sufficient to conclude that affective artificial agents are affective artifacts, at least on the basis of Piredda's (2020) and Viola's (2021) accounts.",
    "However, they are not run-of-the-mill affective artifacts, for they have certain relevant features that make them stand apart from many other \"low-tech\" affective artifacts."
  ]
}